%N A394247 Maximum number of parts i with multiplicity i possible in a partition of n.
%C A394247 This sequence was inspired by a puzzle, "IQ Tests" from the book Mathematical Puzzles and Curiosities. Consider a multiple-choice question: "How many correct answer choices are there: (a) 1, (b) 1, (c) 2, (d) 2?" Answer 2 can be considered correct as it appears twice.
%D A394247 I. David, T. Khovanova, and Y. Shpilman, Mathematical Puzzles and Curiosities, World Scientific, 2026, p.5.
%H A394247 Alois P. Heinz, <a href="/A394247/b394247.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..20539</a>
%F A394247 If n = A000330(k), then a(n) = k. Otherwise, if A000330(k) + k < n <= A000330(k+1) + k+1, then a(n) = k.
%e A394247 Consider the 7 partitions of 5: (1,1,1,1,1),(1,1,1,2),(1,2,2),(1,1,3),(2,3),(1,4), and (5). Only one partition (1,4) has one distinct number appearing the same number of times as itself. Only one partition (1,2,2) has two distinct numbers appearing the same number of times as themselves. The remaining partitions do not have parts appearing the same number of times as themselves. Thus, the maximum number of distinct parts appearing the same number of times as their values, implying that a(5)=2.
%p A394247 b:= proc(n, i, t) option remember; `if`(n=0, t, `if`(i<1, 0,
%p A394247       max(seq(b(n-i*j, i-1, t+`if`(i=j, 1, 0)), j=0..n/i))))
%p A394247     end:
%p A394247 a:= n-> b(n$2,0):
%p A394247 seq(a(n), n=0..107);  # _Alois P. Heinz_, Mar 26 2026
%Y A394247 Cf. A000041, A000330, A276429, A336273, A391611, A392745, A394246.
%K A394247 nonn
